npm error For a full report see:

npm error C:\npm\cache\_logs\2026-05-01T13_16_25_570Z-eresolve-report.txt

npm error A complete log of this run can be found in: C:\npm\cache\_logs\2026-05-01T13_16_25_570Z-debug-0.log

Error: The process 'C:\hostedtoolcache\windows\frogbot\[RELEASE]\x64\frogbot.exe' failed with exit code 1

The error you are seeing is an ERESOLVE issue caused by a peer dependency conflict between elysia and file-type.

The Problem:
Your project is explicitly asking for "file-type": "^18.7.0" in the dependencies of your package.json.

elysia (which you installed with ^1.0.0) requires a newer version of file-type as a peer dependency, specifically ">= 20.0.0".

Because npm strictly enforces peer dependencies by default, it halts the installation when it sees this version mismatch.

How to Fix It:
Option 1: Update the file-type version (Recommended)
Update your package.json to require a version of file-type that satisfies elysia's peer dependency requirement.

Open your package.json, find the file-type entry in your dependencies, and change it to:

JSON
"file-type": "^20.0.0",
Option 2: Force the installation (Not Recommended)
If your project absolutely relies on file-type v18 and you don't mind potentially breaking elysia, you can bypass the strict peer dependency checks. However, since the error is occurring inside a CI/CD pipeline running Frogbot, Option 1 is heavily preferred.

If you are running this locally to generate a package-lock.json first, you would run:

Bash
npm install --legacy-peer-deps
Next Steps:

Update file-type to "^20.0.0" in your package.json.

Delete your package-lock.json and node_modules folder (if you are running this locally).

Run npm install again to generate a clean, conflict-free lockfile.

Commit the changes and let Frogbot run again!

resolve all such conflicts and create an amended package.json file

I have resolved the file-type peer dependency conflict (updating it to "^20.0.0") and wrote the corrected configuration out to a new file named amended_package.json in your current working directory.
