A Note on "All Such Conflicts"
It's important to mention that this package.json contains over 700 dependencies, combining almost every modern framework (React, Vue, Express, Fastify, Next.js, Remix, Hapi) and database ORM available.

Because npm strict peer-dependency resolution evaluates the entire tree recursively against the live npm registry, there are very likely dozens of other hidden peer dependency conflicts in this file that will only surface when you run npm install. Without querying the live npm registry against every package, we can't preemptively fix all of them.

To get this to install successfully:
Use the amended file: Replace your existing package.json with the newly generated amended_package.json.

Clear previous trees: If you have them, delete node_modules and package-lock.json.

If you hit more ERESOLVE errors: Since this is a massive list of competing packages, the quickest way to get it to build in a CI environment (like Frogbot) without manually debugging hundreds of peer conflicts is to run:

Bash
npm install --legacy-peer-deps
If this is meant to be a real production application rather than a test repository, the absolute best way to resolve these conflicts permanently is to drastically prune the dependencies list down to only the exact tools the project is actually using.

